,Not Recommended,260160,29595667,Posted: 30 January,all,Scopedog,"It feels kind of harsh to judge a game on what it isn’t rather than on it’s own terms, but like many others I bought City of Colours on the strength of the description. Inspired by Banjo Kazooie and Jak and Daxter. If you’re going to namedrop to sell, then you can’t be surprised when you’re compared directly to those games.This game shares almost nothing with those classics except for a twee art style. Those games are defined by platforming, collectables and an open structure, where players can take on challenges in whatever order they wish. The Last Tinker is an entirely linear game with no jump button. Platforming challenges consist of nothing more than holding a trigger and moving the stick forwards, similar to Zelda games – it’s almost entirely automated and thus entirely unengaging.The rest of the game consists of tepid, unchallenging puzzles punctuated by perfunctory batman style combat. Occasionally there’s an utterly rote boss fight. I know this is a game aimed at children, but even by those standards the game is coddling and witless. It falls in that uncomfortable middle ground where it’s far too childish for older kids whilst being too mechanically complicated for little ones. If you’re wanting a 3D platformer of old, give this one a miss – it is not what you want it to be."
76561197999631984,Recommended,260160,28790053,"Posted: 29 December, 2016",all,Jazzy,"For two dollars (got it on sale), this is was one hell of a bargain!As almost every other review has stated, this game reminded me of Banjo Kazooie and Crash Bandicoot. Even though the game has a childish nature to it, there are many deep rooted themes that reflect today's society in America. I usually write lengthy reviews with in depth reviews, commentaries, and discussions, I'll keep this one simple and short, much like the game.Pros:Visually nice, reminded me of those old school games, and stuff like Paper Mario.Interesting storyMoral themes reflecting current life and views in AmericaCons:Combat is a little repetitiveShort game (quality over quantity though)Little to no replayabilityOverall, I read quite a few reviews that says the game is perfect to play with a young gamer. I am inclined to agree, however, there are small tidbits where adults will have just as much fun playing it as a kid would. It's like a Pixar movie: designed for kids, but perfectly playable and enjoyable for adults.The only real downside for me is that I do no think the game is worth $20. If it's on sale, I highly recommend you pick it up. Hope you all enjoy it!"
