,Recommended,260160,29062934,Posted: 6 January,all,Lupal Fillyus,"TL;DR: Play this for the atmosphere. ~8 hours. Worth the 2 bucks(xD) I got it for during Winter sale.Numerous games come to mind playing this.Everything by Rareware, Psychonauts, Little Big Planet, Paper Mario. Yes, I'm using the ""it's like <all these great games>"" description that's usually a bit scammy. I'll pick one then, it's like Beyond Good and Evil. Linear, not terribly complex, but downright fun.- It's not a platformer.- Don't expect puzzles. It's just lever-pulling and repeating a sequence.- A bit of (self-)referential humor at times, don't expect a lot.- Linear as all hell, except for a single optional collectible. There's also gems to buy moves with(or as a key item at start), but that happens automatically. There is no backtracking whatsoever. ~8 hours.-- Possible because of this, an excellent hint system. Just ask your buddy and he will fly almost the exact route you need to go.- Combat is not difficult,except for the unlockable, optional arena. I went for the ""instant death"" difficulty, thinking it to be a cooler name for ""nightmare"". It is not. Things will gib you continuously, even things that only knockback on other settings. Does not make the game more fun, just more annoying. No achi either. Just don't.-- The cargo rails. What I thought was a scenic trip through the wonderfully crafted world was instead a quick time event in disquise. Especially on instant death. Bah.-- Enemies(outside of boss adds) do not respawn. Even instant death is quite doable, the regular levels. Bosses still require a lot of trial and error until you completely know the attack pattern.-- You gather three colored powers over the course of the game,but they are simply damage, fear and stun. The first quarter of the game is simply""hit it until it dies, dodge if it attacks"". They also give a superpower usable once a bar is filled. But this doesn't add any depth to boss fights, as they still need to be hit X times in the weak spot.Power, Time Stop and Invulnerability. Bosses remain vulnerable until a third of their hp is damaged, so Power nor Time Stop work. Layme.- It's cartoony. Some people use that as a pejorative, but it's simply a description. Like romantic comedy. Some people never like romantic comedies, most people need to be in a mood for it. Just like with cartoony. It feels cell-shady, everything is bright and un-brown.- ""Everything in this world is made of paint, paper and glue"", and it shows. Text balloons are in gamespace, some are static, so you can view a textbox from the side to see that sinusoid cardboard thing, and you can view them from behind where they're blank.- The world is beautifully made. There's dissapointingly much lore, as you don't ever see e.g. the inside of a dust refinery, or a rainbow factory where colors are made. On the other hand, you can often peer in a random direction and see detail without the quests ever taking you there.- The characters. Banjo-Kazooie-like creatures just ramble on in their voice, gesturing, no matter their actual text. Each race has a ""voice"", and some unique characters have their own. There's quite a few different expressions. The three races look nothing alike, not just their bodies but their districts as well, each has their own architecture. Especially the spirits look great, Green was amazing.It was a fun experience. I loved the characters, I giggled, I facepalmed at the cheesy story, I enjoyed the scenery, I raged at instant death(just don't)."
